To get the current YouTube thumbnail and convert it to Base64 in C#, you'll need to perform the following steps:

1. Get the video ID.
2. Construct the URL for the YouTube thumbnail.
3. Download the thumbnail image.
4. Convert the image to a Base64 string.

First, make sure to install the `System.Net.Http` NuGet package if you haven't already.

Here's a sample C# code to achieve this:
```csharp
using System;
using System.IO;
using System.Net.Http;
using System.Threading.Tasks;
using System.Drawing;
using System.Drawing.Imaging;
using System.Text;

class Program
{
    static async Task Main(string[] args)
    {
        string videoId = "YOUR_VIDEO_ID"; // Replace with your YouTube video ID
        string base64Thumbnail = await GetYouTubeThumbnailAsBase64Async(videoId);
        Console.WriteLine("Base64 Thumbnail: " + base64Thumbnail);
    }

    public static async Task<string> GetYouTubeThumbnailAsBase64Async(string videoId)
    {
        string thumbnailUrl = $"https://img.youtube.com/vi/{videoId}/maxresdefault.jpg";

        using HttpClient client = new HttpClient();
        byte[] imageBytes = await client.GetByteArrayAsync(thumbnailUrl);

        return Convert.ToBase64String(imageBytes);
    }
}
```
Replace `YOUR_VIDEO_ID` with the actual video ID you want to fetch the thumbnail for. The code above will print the Base64 encoded thumbnail image to the console.

Please note that this code snippet assumes that the thumbnail image is available in the `maxresdefault.jpg` resolution. In some cases, you might need to use a different resolution like `0.jpg`, `1.jpg`, `2.jpg`, `3.jpg`, or `hqdefault.jpg`.

I have the following code:

```
useEffect(() => {
 const handleKeyDown = (event) => {
 // Check if the CMD + F key combination was pressed
 if (event.key === "f" && event.metaKey) {
 event.preventDefault();

 setIsShown(true);
 }

 window.addEventListener("keydown", handleKeyDown);

 return () => {
 window.removeEventListener("keydown", handleKeyDown);
 };
 }, [setExclusionFilter]);
```

It shows the new state on Mac but on Windows it doesn't trigger. How can I support windows?

On Windows, the key that is used in combination with the "Ctrl" key is usually the "F" key. In order to support both Mac and Windows, you can check for both "metaKey" (which is the equivalent of the "Command" key on Mac) and "ctrlKey" (which is the equivalent of the "Ctrl" key on Windows) like this:
```
if (event.key === "f" && (event.metaKey || event.ctrlKey)) {
  event.preventDefault();
  setIsShown(true);
}
```
This way, the code will work on both Mac and Windows if the user presses the "F" key in combination with either the "Command" key on Mac or the "Ctrl" key on Windows.

Here's a sample Terraform data block to query the latest Amazon Machine Image (AMI) for Ubuntu 22.04:
```sql
data "aws_ami" "ubuntu_2204" {
  most_recent = true

  filter {
    name   = "name"
    values = ["ubuntu/images/hvm-ssd/ubuntu-focal-22.04-amd64-server-*"]
  }

  filter {
    name   = "virtualization-type"
    values = ["hvm"]
  }
}

resource "aws_instance" "web" {
  ami           = data.aws_ami.ubuntu_2204.id
  instance_type = "t2.micro"
}
```
This code uses the `data` block to query the latest AMI that matches the filter criteria: `ubuntu/images/hvm-ssd/ubuntu-focal-22.04-amd64-server-*` and `virtualization-type = hvm`. The `aws_ami` data source returns the latest image ID, which is stored in `data.aws_ami.ubuntu_2204.id`. This value is then referenced in the `ami` argument of the `aws_instance.web` resource to launch an EC2 instance based on the latest Ubuntu 22.04 AMI.
